Kevin,

It may be due to the Mac vs. PC line endings in text files.  If the XML 
file was generated on a PC, then each line ends with &lt;CR&gt;&lt;LF&gt;.  On unix 
or Mac systems, only one character is used to denote the end of line, 
leaving one extraneous character.  Cantera&#39;s XML parser may not handle 
such cross-platform text files correctly.  From the error message, I am 
guessing that the species string has an extraneous, non-printing 
character that is being interpreted as a species name.

If Cantera can read correctly the input CTI or XML files that come with 
Cantera, then it is some problem with that XML file, likely to be the 
line-ending problem.  I will take a look at the code and see if this 
seems to be the issue, and if it can be made more robust.

The best bet is to use the CTI input file, which will automatically 
generate a new copy of the XML file, but this time with line endings 
correct for the Mac.

Dave


